          "number": 29278,
          "state": "open",
          "state_reason": null,
          "title": "RPC: Wallet:  Add `maxfeerate` and `maxburnamount` startup option",
          "body": "This PR attempts to fix two issues\r\n\r\n#29217\r\n#29220\r\n\r\nFirstly,\r\n- Both `sendrawtransaction` and `testmempoolaccept` have the optional parameter `maxfeerate`. \r\nWhen passed, this parameter ensures that any transactions with a fee rate higher than the specified `maxfeerate` value are rejected.\r\n\r\n- `maxburnamount` is also an optional parameter for `sendrawtransaction`. When passed, it rejects transactions with unspendable outputs (e.g., 'datacarrier' outputs using the OP_RETURN opcode) greater than the specified value.\r\n\r\n- The newly introduced RPC, `submitpackage`, will also incorporate these sanity checks and support the same optional parameters of `maxfeerate` and `maxburnamount` as a sanity check.\r\n\r\n- This PR introduces two new startup config options: \r\n`maxfeerate` and `maxburnamount`.\r\n\r\n- This eliminates the need to pass them explicitly in every RPC call. \r\n\r\n- Instead, `maxfeerate` and `maxburnamount` values passed in a startup will be used by `sendrawtransaction` RPC and friends.\r\n\r\nSecondly \r\n- In some instances within the wallet, as indicated in #29220, where \t`maxtxfee` serves as a quantifier for the maximum fee rate of a transaction. This PR fixes the issue by using the new value passed in the `maxfeerate` startup option as a quantifier instead of maxtxfee.\r\n\r\n- However, this adds the default behaviour of `maxfeerate` to the wallet, meaning if users specify a 0 for `maxfeerate`, the wallet will accept transactions with any fee rate.\r\n\r\nThis approach maintains distinct role for `maxfeerate` as a wallet and mempool acceptance/relay sanity check instead of creating another option for the wallet.",
